0/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Department for Transport: Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which (a) parliamentary constituencies he visited and (b) hon. Members he met with in their constituencies during the 2017 summer recess; what the dates were of those visits; and which proposed or current transport schemes he visited in that period.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","9096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758291","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>Rail commuters into Manchester will benefit from an almost 30% increase in capacity on Northern services in the morning peak and for rail commuters into Leeds a 37% increase. By December 2019, an extra 18 Northern services per day will be introduced.</p><p> </p><p>On Sundays 2 trains per hour will be provided, up from 1 per hour today, and new hourly services to Manchester Airport and Liverpool via Manchester using brand new trains.</p><p> </p><p>Between Bradford and Leeds, a new direct link will be introduced to Wakefield, Sheffield, Chesterfield and Nottingham via Leeds, with at least 10 services per day in each direction operated by brand new diesel trains.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758291/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T15:01:28.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758291/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758291/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to increase passenger capacity on trains between Bradford and (a) Manchester and (b) Leeds.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","9170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758293","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>HS2 Ltd have not worked with the Cabinet Office Behavioural Insight Team.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","9221","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758293/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T13:52:43.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758293/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758293/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether HS2 Limited has worked with the Behavioural Insights Team.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758294","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department for Transport has received services, and worked with, the Cabinet Office’s Behavioural Insights team in connection with High Speed 2. This has enabled the department to add to its evidence base regarding the impacts of the project.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","9218","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758294/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T13:59:44.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758294/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758294/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has received services from the Behavioural Insights Team on High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758295","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>HS2 Ltd have not worked with the Cabinet Office Behavioural Insight Team.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","9219","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758295/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T13:52:44.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758295/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758295/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether High Speed 2 has received services from the Behavioural Insights Team.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758296","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department for Transport has received services, and worked with, the Cabinet Office’s Behavioural Insights team in connection with High Speed 2. This has enabled the department to add to its evidence base regarding the impacts of the project.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","9220","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758296/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T13:59:44.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758296/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758296/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Behavioural Insights Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has worked with the Behavioural Insights Team on High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758300","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>Approximately £380m has been spent to date on the upgrade of the Midland Main Line. This includes approximately £305m on the section of the route between London to Corby (on electrification work and related infrastructure upgrades), and approximately £30m on preliminary works north of Kettering, including the raising of bridges on that part of the route. This will allow any future upgrade to be carried out with as little disruption as possible. The remainder of this spend has been on infrastructure upgrades across the route, including designing and developing works at Market Harborough and in Derby.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758300/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T15:18:39.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758300/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758300/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been spent to date on the electification of the Midland Mainline (a) in total, (b) London to Corby and (c) north of Kettering.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","9223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758301","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The amount spent by HS2 Ltd staff on rail travel from June 2013 to date is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Standard Train Spend (£)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>First Class Train Spend (£)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Train Spend (£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2013- March 2014</p></td><td><p>269,811.40</p></td><td><p>1,056.80</p></td><td><p>270,868.20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2014 – March 2015</p></td><td><p>462,099.37</p></td><td><p>1,465.75</p></td><td><p>463,565.12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2015 – March 2016</p></td><td><p>1,202,504.59</p></td><td><p>361.00</p></td><td><p>1,202,865.59</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2016 – March 2017</p></td><td><p>2,344,578.80</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>2,344,578.80</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2017 – 31<sup>st</sup> July 2017</p></td><td><p>975,473.05</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>975,473.05</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>5,254,467.21</p></td><td><p>2,883.55</p></td><td><p>5,257,350.76</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Since 2015, first class rail travel has been prohibited by HS2.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to June 2013 rail travel expenses for HS2 Ltd staff were recorded on a different accounting system. On this system they were not separated from other staff expenses. As such, we cannot provide expenses associated with rail travel alone prior to June 2013.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758301/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T15:13:04.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758301/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758301/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been spent on (a) all, (b) standard train and (c) first class train travel by staff of HS2 Ltd in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","9164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758302","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>Northern Rail will be introducing, by December 2019, faster inter-urban services serving Leeds and Manchester from Bradford, operating with 100mph trains.</p><p> </p><p>As part of their franchise commitments, Northern will undertake a feasibility study to identify options for delivering journey time improvements.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758302/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T15:31:51.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758302/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758302/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to reduce train journey times between Bradford and (a) Manchester and (b) Leeds.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","9169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758303","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-15","<p>The Department for Transport take account of the needs of all groups in developing its policies and delivering its services. The department aims to make all its information and correspondence accessible and responds positively to requests for information in different formats, including British Sign Language. We have a policy of fulfilling reasonable requests where costs are proportionate.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758303/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-15T09:39:47.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758303/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758303/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Department for Transport: Sign Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department takes to provide (a) information on its services in British Sign Language (BSL) and (b) correspondence in BSL to people whose principal language is BSL.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","9011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758304","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Network Rail is delivering the Great Western Electrification Programme to the dates set out in the latest publication of their Enhancement Delivery plan.</p><p> </p><p>This includes completing electrification of the Great Western Mainline to Cardiff Central by December 2018. The recent National Audit Office’s report states that electrification is expected to cost £2.8 billion.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail have advised the Department that expenditure on the mainline between Cardiff and Swansea has yet to be finalised.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758304/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-14T13:49:06.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758304/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758304/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Railways: South Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost to the public purse has been of electrification of the railway line (a) in the Severn Tunnel, (b) between the Severn Tunnel and Cardiff Central station, (c) between Cardiff Central Station and Bridgend, (d) between Bridgend and Port Talbot Parkway, (e) between Port Talbot Parkway and Neath and (f) between Neath and Swansea; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","9045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758305","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Government takes the safety risks of drones to transport very seriously. We have already taken action on the misuse of drones by improving enforcement of the law, resulting in several successful drone prosecutions. Following consultation, the Government announced in July that it will introduce a registration scheme to increase the accountability of users, explore the potential of raising penalties for current offences and review the powers available to law enforcement agencies to enforce the law.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the flying of drones near sensitive sites is already prohibited. Government has been undertaking a programme of work aimed at improving our defences against drones, with a focus on sensitive and important locations and events. This includes exploration of technological options to detect and counter drones, with trials and demonstrations taking place in order to examine the applicability of various technological options to do so.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758305/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-14T11:00:29.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758305/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758305/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to prevent the deliberate use of drones to disrupt transport.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","9075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758306","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government Car Service will be replacing diesel vehicles on their fleet as they become due for replacement with non-diesel alternatives. It has so far replaced a quarter of its vehicles with petrol hybrid cars. There is no specific target date for this to be completed, it will be dependent on an assessment at time of renewal in the interests of maximising value for money.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758306/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T09:34:32.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758306/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758306/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Official Cars: Diesel Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, by what date it is planned that the Government Car Service no longer uses diesel vehicles.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","9264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758307","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-14","<p>Stirling station was included in the original Access for All programme but no solution to provide access to every platform could be found. The funding was therefore reallocated to other stations in Scotland. We are seeking new money to extend Access for All beyond 2019. If this is successful we will be asking the industry for new station nominations next year.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758307/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-14T13:53:47.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758307/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758307/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-06","Stirling Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has received an application to the Access for All programme for funding for platform nine at Stirling station; and if he will meet the hon. Member for Ochil and South Perthshire the effect of lack of accessibility at that station on residents of Ochil and South Perthshire constituency.","false","Biography information for Luke Graham","Ochil and South Perthshire","Luke Graham","9212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758308","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The requested information for Personal Independence Payment (PIP) applications is not available as information on PIP claimants’ disabling conditions is not collected at the initial claim application stage. Only those who have a disability assessment determination decision will have a primary disabling condition recorded for them. The Department does not therefore hold data on the number of individuals with a particular condition who make a claim for PIP.</p><p> </p><p>The latest available data on PIP claims in payment, including by main disabling condition and geography (e.g. local authority), are published on Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p>These data relate to the claimant’s main disabling condition. Claimants may often have multiple disabling conditions, but these cannot be identified from the data the department holds. Therefore there may be other claimants in receipt of PIP who have been diagnosed with a mental health illness who are not captured in the above data.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758308/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T12:45:16.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758308/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758308/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-06","Personal Independence Payment: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claims for personal independence payment in the London Borough of Southwark have been due to a mental health illness in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","9024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758309","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>There are no current plans to meet with representatives of the Women Against State Pension Inequality campaign in the immediate future.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This matter has been comprehensively debated on many occasions in Parliament, most recently in a Westminster Hall Debate on 5th July 2017 in which I stated I will be meeting the All Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) when it is reformed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758309/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T12:40:17.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758309/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758309/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-06","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will meet the hon. Member for Coventry North East and a delegation from WASPI Coventry to discuss changes to the state pension age for women born in the 1950s.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","9078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758310","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The table below shows the number of appeals lodged against Personal Independence Payment claims which were disallowed at initial decision and where this decision was upheld at mandatory reconsideration, the number of these appeals where a decision has been made and the number of these appeals that were subsequently successful for the appellant, for the London Borough of Southwark over the last five years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year of appeal lodgement</p></td><td><p>Number of appeals lodged</p></td><td><p>Number of appeals with a decision</p></td><td><p>Number of successful appeals (for the appellant)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>#</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>150</p></td><td><p>140</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>180</p></td><td><p>170</p></td><td><p>130</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017 (to April ’17)</p></td><td><p>80</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>420</p></td><td><p>390</p></td><td><p>270</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>‘# ‘used for instances where there are less than 5 cases to avoid the release of confidential data</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758310/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-11T13:10:10.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758310/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758310/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-06","Personal Independence Payment: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in the London Borough of Southwark have appealed against his Department's decision not to grant them personal independence payment in each of the last five years; and how many of those appeals have been successful in those years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","9023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758311","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-15","<p>a) The Department is obliged to anticipate the communication needs of any customer who would otherwise be placed at substantial disadvantage and to put in place an alternative format of communication which will meet the customer’s needs. The Department is currently only able to provide general information on GOV.UK regarding its services. We are able to provide services in BSL when requested by our customers.</p><p> </p><p>b) DWP customers who have a specific communication barrier are able to use a variety of communication methods including home visits, phone calls and online services as well as written communications. Once we have established that a customer uses BSL as their principal form of communication with the Department, all future correspondence with that customer will be arranged in this form, without the need for repeated requests. Where necessary the department provides British Sign Language (BSL) interpreters or non-spoken language interpreters, using contracted providers for customers who are deaf, hard of hearing or speech impaired. Video relay service (VRS) is also being trialed through the call centres for Disability Living Allowance, Attendance Allowance and Access to Work, as well as by the Access to Work advisers in the Hearing Loss Team. VRS allows users to make BSL interpreted video calls via their tablet, smartphone, computer or laptop. A professional interpreter then relays the call in English to a member of DWP staff.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758311/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-15T11:27:36.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758311/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758311/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-06","Department for Work and Pensions: Sign Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department takes to provide (a) information on its services in British Sign Language (BSL) and (b) correspondence in BSL to people whose principal language is BSL.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","9013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758312","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Government is committed to improving employment outcomes for disabled people. The manifesto commitment gives a clear and time-bound goal to achieve this, which is to see 1 million more disabled people into work over the next 10 years.</p><p> </p><p>Since quarter 1 2016, the number of working aged disabled people in employment has increased by around 170,000 to 3.5 million in quarter 1 2017. The disability employment rate has increased by over 2 percentage points and now stands at 49 per cent.</p><p> </p><p>The number of disabled people in employment, according to the Labour Force Survey, is publicly available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/datasets/labourmarketstatusofdisabledpeoplea08" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/datasets/labourmarketstatusofdisabledpeoplea08</a></p><p> </p><p>We know that there is much more that needs to be done, so that everyone who can work is given the right support and opportunities to do so. That is why we published Improving Lives: the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper, which set out the action we plan to take to achieve this and start a far-reaching, national debate on what more we can do to ensure everyone is supported to reach their full potential. We are considering next steps, taking account of the Green Paper consultation, and will set out our response to this and future plans in due course, including supporting local effort and reporting arrangements.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","9244 ; 9245","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758312/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-14T09:53:10.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758312/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758312/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-06","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to report annually to Parliament on progress in tackling the disability employment gap as part of the annual report on full employment.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","9126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758313","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>The Government is committed to improving employment outcomes for disabled people. The manifesto commitment gives a clear and time-bound goal to achieve this, which is to see 1 million more disabled people into work over the next 10 years.</p><p> </p><p>Since quarter 1 2016, the number of working aged disabled people in employment has increased by around 170,000 to 3.5 million in quarter 1 2017. The disability employment rate has increased by over 2 percentage points and now stands at 49 per cent.</p><p> </p><p>The number of disabled people in employment, according to the Labour Force Survey, is publicly available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/datasets/labourmarketstatusofdisabledpeoplea08" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/datasets/labourmarketstatusofdisabledpeoplea08</a></p><p> </p><p>We know that there is much more that needs to be done, so that everyone who can work is given the right support and opportunities to do so. That is why we published Improving Lives: the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper, which set out the action we plan to take to achieve this and start a far-reaching, national debate on what more we can do to ensure everyone is supported to reach their full potential. We are considering next steps, taking account of the Green Paper consultation, and will set out our response to this and future plans in due course, including supporting local effort and reporting arrangements.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","9126 ; 9244","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758313/answer",,,,,,,,,"2017-09-14T09:53:10.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758313/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758313/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Wor